CASE
❓ Question:

You’re given a messy dataset to build a pricing model.
The data has missing values, inconsistent formats, and unclear variables.
How would you approach building a robust model?


✅ ✅ What interviewers want to see
They are testing:

Structured thinking ✅
Data judgement ✅
Modelling rigour ✅
Governance awareness ✅
Practical experience ✅


🧠 ✅ GOLD STANDARD STRUCTURE

1. Understand problem → 2. Data cleaning → 3. Exploratory analysis → 4. Feature engineering → 5. Modelling → 6. Validation → 7. Deployment & monitoring


🧠 ✅ MODEL ANSWER (TECHNICAL + SENIOR)
🔹 1. Problem definition (ALWAYS start here)

First, I would clarify the business objective and modelling target.


What are we predicting?

Frequency? Severity? Pure premium?


What’s the time horizon?
Any constraints?

Regulatory / fairness / explainability



👉 This avoids building the wrong model

🔹 2. Data cleaning & preprocessing (critical with messy data)
A. Data quality assessment

Missing values
Duplicates
Inconsistent formats (e.g. dates, categories)
Outliers


B. Missing data handling
Different strategies depending on variable:


Numeric:

Mean/median imputation
Model-based imputation



Categorical:

Create “missing” category



👉 Important:

Missingness itself can be predictive


C. Outlier treatment

Winsorisation
Capping
Investigate if real vs error


D. Consistency checks

Standardise:

Categories (e.g. "M", "Male")


Remove duplicates
Fix data leakage

👉 Example leakage:

Using future claims data


🔹 3. Exploratory data analysis (EDA)
A. Univariate analysis

Distributions
Skewness


B. Bivariate analysis

Relationship between features and target

For pricing:

Claims frequency vs age
Severity vs vehicle type


C. Correlation analysis

Identify:

Multicollinearity (GLM issue)




👉 Output:

Early hypothesis on key drivers


🔹 4. Feature engineering (where seniority shows)
A. Transformations

Log transforms (for severity)
Binning (e.g. age bands)


B. Interaction terms

Age × vehicle
Region × risk factors


C. Encoding

One-hot encoding (categorical)
Target encoding (with care → leakage risk)


D. Feature selection (important for GDPR)

Remove:

Redundant variables
Proxy variables



👉 Always ask:

Is this variable necessary and justifiable?


🔹 5. Modelling approach
A. Start simple and interpretable

GLM:

Frequency → Poisson
Severity → Gamma
Combined → Tweedie



👉 Why:

Transparent
Industry standard
Easy to explain


B. Benchmark models

Compare:

GLM vs ML models (e.g. GBM, XGBoost)




C. Regularisation

Lasso / Ridge:

Prevent overfitting
Stabilise coefficients




D. Model selection criteria

Performance metrics
Explainability
Regulatory acceptability


🔹 6. Validation (don’t skip details)
A. Train-test split / cross-validation

Time-based split (if relevant)


B. Performance metrics

Gini
RMSE / deviance
Calibration plots


C. Stability checks

Across segments
Sensitivity analysis


D. Fairness checks

Segment-level outcomes
Identify bias


👉 This is where many candidates are weak—mentioning fairness puts you ahead

🔹 7. Model governance & documentation


Document:

Data sources
Assumptions
Feature selection
Limitations



Ensure:

Auditability
Explainability




🔹 8. Deployment & monitoring
A. Monitoring setup

Performance drift
Data drift (PSI)
Business KPIs (loss ratio, conversion)


B. Feedback loop

Retraining schedule
Alerts for anomalies


🎤 💬 “Top-tier” concise answer
If you need a clean version:

I would start by clearly defining the modelling objective and target variable. Given messy data, I would prioritise data cleaning, including handling missing values, standardising formats, and addressing outliers and potential data leakage.
I would then perform exploratory analysis to understand key drivers and relationships, followed by feature engineering, including transformations, interactions, and careful feature selection to avoid redundancy or proxy bias.
For modelling, I would begin with an interpretable approach such as a GLM, benchmarking against more complex models if appropriate, while balancing performance and explainability.
I would validate the model using appropriate performance metrics, calibration checks, and stability analysis across segments, including fairness considerations.
Finally, I would ensure strong documentation, deploy the model with monitoring for performance and data drift, and establish a feedback loop for ongoing improvement.


